# Gitleaks false positives, ignored by exact finding fingerprint
# (format: <commit>:<path>:<rule>:<line> — scoped to one finding each, so a
# real secret in any other commit/file/line still fails the scan).
#
# .github/workflows/eval.yml wrote a placeholder service-account JSON to disk so
# the Vertex AI client would initialize in CI. The "private key" is a truncated
# PKCS#8 header (~52 chars vs ~1700 for a real RSA key), project_id "dummy",
# client_email dummy@dummy.iam.gserviceaccount.com. It never authenticated
# against anything. The gitleaks private-key rule matches the BEGIN PRIVATE KEY
# marker regardless of whether the payload is a valid key, hence the hit.
#
# The workflow itself was deleted in b593142, but these commits remain in history
# and a full-history scan (what the weekly schedule runs) keeps re-finding them.
